{{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 | color = black |name = Kobori Nanrei Sōhaku |image= Kobori Nanrei Sohaku.JPG |caption = |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = 1918 |birth_place = [[Japan]] |death_date = 1992 |death_place = |nationality = |religion = [[Rinzai]] |school = |lineage = |title = [[Rōshi|Roshi]] |location = Ryōkōin |education = |occupation = |teacher = |reincarnation of = |predecessor = |successor = |students = [[James H. Austin]] |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = }} {{nihongo|'''Kobori Nanrei Sōhaku'''|小堀 南嶺}} (1918—1992) was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[Rinzai]] [[Rōshi|roshi]] and former abbot of Ryōkōin, a subtemple of [[Daitoku-ji]] in [[Kyoto, Japan]].<ref name="levine">Levine, xliii</ref> A student of the late [[Daisetz Teitaro Suzuki]],<ref>Franck, 84</ref> Sōhaku was fluent in [[English language|English]][http://www.ithaca.edu/news/release.php?id=2395] and known to hold regular [[sesshin]]s until the 1980s which many [[United States|Americans]] attended.<ref name="levine"/> One of his American students is [[James H. Austin]], author of ''Zen and the Brain''.[http://www.ithaca.edu/news/release.php?id=2395] Austin writes of his teacher, "This remarkable person, Kobori-roshi, inspired me to begin the long path of Zen and stick to it. As a result, I have since continued to repair my ignorance about Zen and its psychophysiology during an ongoing process of adult reeducation."<ref>Austin, 175</ref>
